eground and background without resetting. For example, in the string \\\"A true fore B true back C\\\", char C needs both color masks. If I avoid resetting after combining, I should also consider whether a foreground reset is necessary. My current implementation uses color resets that might lose combined coverage, so perhaps I'll preserve that instead. I'll ensure tests maintain proper coverage without unnecessary resets.\\n\\n**Examining color parsing**\\n\\nI'm analyzing the parsing of colors, specifically how \\\"A...B\\\\u001b[48;2;1;2;3mC\\\" interacts with the plain \\\"ABC.\\\" The color retrieval functions seem to yield a correct foreground and background without introducing reset failures. This approach helps maintain coverage by ensuring both colors are parsed together, instead of just the background. Still, I wonder if using `parsed.getColor(2)` to compare the combined attributes would better address potential issues. Also, I need to rethink whether to keep the foreground reset for improved testing coverage.\\n\\n**Analyzing functional coverage**\\n\\nI'm considering which functional coverage is greater. The original implementation combines true foreground and background colors, but the reset after the true background seems to break. I wonder if I can keep the reset after the true foreground separate instead. The idea of parsing a string like \\\"A true fore B foreground reset C true foreground+back D\\\" feels a bit complex. Maybe it’s better not to complicate things further. I need to find a balance in coverage without overcomplicating the parsing process.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_05ce9e1aa005ba62016a2355d1449c8195ab23401f41f59f1e\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"content\\\":[],\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqI1Xki4iXKtIJa3BVbGQ20cWkkMI4NKmQD5qNAsOQUEzUdhkmFTWwfB0m7fkZHsjeP7ocL_7l3R95A73gwaDEliHm25Aussrl02efY6sl0VQy8Sox-WilxvmJc51euqYUEltLnEuiYhxVdXXuVoPAbyPfczIQLdElfIZb2Y78X_OGzeercnowESc8TczY1rv9TpJfrj4lxsLtJTvGL3mMHh