NTh1oRSlXJYJx5j_3WJDlOtfMsRg3_xlBlEKbkCqNmBrL5N3npApsYhMayLxknaXBd0GfdbAHo7YwIMUfTisigDCmNO9iFPvGFo8R2EOssyX16mXCO2x24saPktR-747W3ZOXdGeGy3h3a9rh76Mocp7TsU4Lv8PleF6aODMejnie9iEiz7Dd290m_JhOjuGvqQpR0Tz9eBondz_gqXfLxyzoUlArwe9nCTVuTB10MFNE8dy5M2ZNWHUhq5TAl-E3reQOqiJ0FNSL7C3WMnEtHTfVKwDyxTWp4wvbIDK5HEqn2Gkg_LCXLZzpC3q7vpq0zZWBJXFMNEFZSV1RT7I8-rl3jGvTT3KeCP4d20II1ngRcUrochvOORCFWTdoRa26VWD9vF3PK-rcZmiu-P7LWDzkefQNfb7f_aFSHxynlfet62F2FteNaa4veDtQXG2Jxdnnjq_zjQ==\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering background parsing**\\\\n\\\\nI'm pondering the implications of changing the true background parse string. It seems crucial to test the combined foreground and background without resetting. For example, in the string \\\\\\\"A true fore B true back C\\\\\\\", char C needs both color masks. If I avoid resetting after combining, I should also consider whether a foreground reset is necessary. My current implementation uses color resets that might lose combined coverage, so perhaps I'll preserve that instead. I'll ensure tests maintain proper coverage without unnecessary resets.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Examining color parsing**\\\\n\\\\nI'm analyzing the parsing of colors, specifically how \\\\\\\"A...B\\\\\\\\u001b[48;2;1;2;3mC\\\\\\\" interacts with the plain \\\\\\\"ABC.\\\\\\\" The color retrieval functions seem to yield a correct foreground and background without introducing reset failures. This approach helps maintain coverage by ensuring both colors are parsed together, instead of just the background. Still, I wonder if using `parsed.getColor(2)` to compare the combined attributes would better address potential issues. Also, I need to rethink whether to keep the foreground reset for improved testing coverage.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Analyzing functional coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering which functional coverage is greater. The original implementation combines true foreground and background colors, but the reset after the true background seems to break. I wonder if I can keep the reset after the true foreground separate instead. The idea of parsing a string like \\\\\\\"A true fore B foreground reset C true foreground+back D\\\\\\\" feels a bit complex. Maybe it’s better not to complicate things further. I need to find a balance in coverage without overcomplicating the parsing process.\\\"}]}\"},{\"type\":\"toolCall\",\"id\":\"call_QvyxbbqI6XzYe53i69LOBdx6|fc_05ce9e1aa005ba62016a2355e47f0081959249cdacd2467351\",\"name\":\"edit\",\"arguments\":{\"path\":\"tests/src/com.lihaoyi/fansi_3/0.5.1/src/test/scala/com_lihaoyi/fansi_3/Fansi_3Test.scala\",\"edits\":[{\"oldText\":\"    val parsed: Str = Str.Throw(\\\"A\\\\u001b[38;2;12;34;56mB\\\\u001b[39mC\\\\u001b[48;2;1;2;3mD\\\")\\n    assertEquals(\\\"ABCD\\\", parsed.plainText)\\n    assertEquals(0L, parsed.getColor(0))\\n    assertEquals(Color.True(12, 34, 56).transform(0L), parsed.getColor(1))\\n    assertEquals(0L, parsed.getColor(2))\\n    assertEquals(Back.True(1, 2, 3).transform(0L), parsed.getColor(3))\\n    assertNotEquals(parsed.getColor(1), parsed.getColor(3))\\n\",\"newText\":\"    val parsed: Str = Str.Throw(\\\"A\\\\u001b[38;2;12;34;56mB\\\\u001b[48;2;1;2;3mC\\\")\\n    val combinedTrueColors: Long = (Color.True(12, 34, 56) ++ Back.True(1, 2, 3)).transform(0L)\\n    assertEquals(\\\"ABC\\\", parsed.plainText)\\n    assertEquals(0L, parsed.getColor(0))\\n    assertEquals(Color.True(12, 34, 56).transform(0L), parsed.getColor(1))\\n    assertEquals(combinedTrueColors, parsed.getColor(2))\\n    assertNotEquals(parsed.getColor(1), parsed.getColor(2))\\n\"}]}}],\"api\":\"openai-responses\",\"provider\":\"OCA\",\"model\":\"oca/gpt-5.5\",\"usage\":{\"input\":1373,\"output\":1308,\"cacheRead\":30720,\"cacheWrite\":0,\"totalTokens\":33401,\"cost\":{\"input\":0,\"output\":0,\"cacheRead\":0,\"cacheWrite\":0,\"total\":0}},\"stopReason\":\"toolUse\",\"timestamp\":178070062